You’re pointing at another failure mode: accountability systems can be gamed not only by officials dodging questions, but also by questioners using bad-faith tactics to manufacture outrage rather than get information.

A system built for accountability would probably need standards on both sides:

* Questions must be clear and specific — avoid loaded premises (“When did you stop doing X?” when X wasn’t established).
* No compound traps — one question at a time.
* Distinguish fact questions from opinion questions.
* Officials cannot dodge legitimate questions.
* Questioners cannot deliberately misquote, deceptively edit, or frame false assumptions as facts.
* Context requirements — quote full answers, not selectively clipped fragments.
* Correction mechanism — public corrections carry visibility similar to the original claim.

The challenge is punishment. Once governments punish “bad framing” directly, you can run into free speech problems and political abuse (“everyone I dislike asked an abusive question”).

A safer design is often:

* transparency,
* standardized formats,
* independent moderation rules,
* public records,
* correction systems,
* reputation consequences,

rather than broad punishment power.

A useful principle could be:

“No dodging. No deception. No trap framing. No selective editing. Everyone plays by the same rules.”